{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_kodiakriverotter_ver02/data/sn95060049/00513680053/1910063001/0187.xml":{"full_text":"HOTEL ACCOMMODATIONS\nARE BEINC IMPROVED\nWhen the improvements now under\nway and under immediate contempla\ntion are completed there will no longer j\nbe any room for complaint that Tanana\ndoes not possess adequate hotel accom\nmodations.\nThe town\u2019s central location makes it a\nstopping place for all classes of people\nwho have occasion to travel in interior\nAlaska. Nothing is more calculated to\ngive a had impression of a place than\npoor and forbidding hotels, and Tanana\u2019s\nhotels have not been up to a very high\nstandard. The condition was fully rec\nognized, and is being speedily and ef\nfectually remedied.\nThe Tower House.\nJoe Anicich was one of the first to\nmake a move for betterment, and the\nresult is the Tower House, a hotel that\nwould be creditable to a city of several\nthousand people. The rooms of this\nfine place have just been opened to the\npublic and are the perfection of comfort\nand repose. High ceilings, generous\nsize, wide halls, every arrangement was\nmade with the object in view of afford\ning a thorough ventilation Steam heat\nand sanitary plumbing will be installed\nas quickly as circumstances will permit,\nand every appointment of the establish\nment will be brought to a high standard\nof modern excellence.\nMr. Anicich commenced the erection\nof the Tower House last year, when\nbusiness depression was widespread and\nthe outlook for the country and the\ntown was not the brightest. Then peo\nple shook their heads and said his en\nergy was misdirected. Now there are\nfew who hold that opinion.\nThe Kentucky.\nWith his usual keen business foresight\nEd Y. Lee recently secured control of\nthe Kentucky and is remodeling that\nwell-known house in a manner that will\nscarcely leave it recognizable to its for\nmer patrons. It is his purpose to put it\non a firm footing as a strictly first-class\nhotel. All who are acquainted with\nLee\u2019s thorough way of doing things will\nbe assured that the Kentucky will merit\nand receive a large amount of public\nfavor.\nMr. Lee has purchased the Golden\nNorth building from Charles Chanquist\nand is removing it to the lot just east of\nits present site, recently acquired from\nW. C. Brown. G. Brown is now asso\nciated with him in the Golden North\nrestaurant.\nThe Grand.\nIt is the purpose of Mr. Chanquist to\nenlarge the Grand Hotel building and\nextend it over the ground now occupied\nby the Golden North. Another story\nwill be added to the Grand and when\nthe work is completed it will probably\nbe the largest hotel building in Tatiana.\nThe carrying out of these plans may be\ndelayed somewhat on account of the in\nability to secure lumber.\nFrom the foregoing it may be seen\nthat instead of being destitute of up-to\ndate hotels, Tanana may soon become\ndistinguished for having the very best\nhotel accommodations of any town of its\nsize in the entire north.\nMining Expert on Duty.\nDr. Ernest Horstinann, C. E., M. E.,\nwho has been in the district several clays\nfor the purpose of examining the min\ning property of Col. George F. Cooke in i\nthe Gold Mountain district, came up I\nfrom Grant creek last Monday. He is\nreturning to the Gold Mountain district!\ntoday. j\nDr. Horstinann expressed surprise at\nthe showing made by a superficial inves\ntigation of the ground in that region,\nbut said that a closer inquiry is neces\nsary before a final verdict can be pro\nnounced upon it. He was present when\nAllen Fox cleaned up four ounces of\ngold from a 4-point thaw on No. 3above.\nOn his return to the district Dr.\nHorstinann will critically examine the\nground on Grant creek and will also in\nvestigate the conditions on Mason. He\nsays he has not yet procured sufficient\nevidence on which to base a final judg\nment of the property, but thinks he will\nknow the facts before he is through.\n_ Returning to Mason Creek.\nIt is learned that Coloumbe brothers,\nwho joined in the stampede to the Idit\na: od a few weeks ago, are returning to\nMason creek, Gold Mountain district.\nCame From the Old Man.\nPete Pemberton, who wintered in the\nregion commonly designated as the Old\nMan, arrived from that country the\nfirst of the week. He said that Bob\nBuchan and Joe Shaw, who recently left\nXanana for the Old Man, found the\ncamp of St. Peter and lvenally without\nany trouble.\nMr. Pemberton is well known as a\nprospector in the Rampart-Hot Springs\nregion, and was formerly engineer on\nthe old steamer Xunivak. He has now\ngone into the Sullivan district. He\nthinks so well of the Old Man country\nthat he will return and winter there\nagain next winter.\nTry the new barber at the Gibbon shop.\nSalmon is Now King.\nThe first king salmon of the season\nwas brought into Tanana last Tuesday\nfrom Abe\u2019s camp, near The Rapids.\nThey were brought down by Harry Doty\nand were three in number, not very\nlarge, but duly appreciated by those\nfortunate enough to annex a mess of\nthem.\nHeadquarters for the Traveling Public\nPioneer and Tower Houses\nTwo First-class Resorts\nThe Rooms just fitted up and furnished at the Tower House may cost a\nlittle more\u2014they are certain to afford a lot more comfort\nthan can be had at other places.\nJoe Anicich, Prop. Tanana, Alaska\nTHE TANANA RESTAORANT\nBest Meals in the Camp\nShort Orders at All Hours\nBest of everything on the Market. Service unexcelled in the North\nFresh and Delicious Bread, Pies and Pastries Always on Hand\nNATIVES ASK\nCOMMISSIONER\nQUESTIONS\nLast Friday a delegation of about\ntwenty Indians, representing different\ncommunities on the Tanana and Yukon\nrivers, called on United States Commis\nsioner Phil Gallaher. The visit did not\nmean to them the discharge of an im\nplied social obligation, or even the ex\npression of a warm feeling of personal\nfriendship, so much as it did the put\nting to the great United States govern\nment, through its most potent repre\nsentative within their reach, a clean-cut\nbusiness proposition.\nThey wanted to inquire why it is that\nthey are not permitted to enter into\ncontracts for rafting wood down the\nrivers and delivering it to the military\narm of the government at Fort Gibbon,\nat a sure profit to themselves and a pos\nsible saving to the people of the United\nStates, whose wards they now are and\nwhose resources are so sorely taxed\nin circumventing their schemes for sat\nisfying an overpowering craving for\nskookum water. Several years ago, the\nspokesmen of the delegation said, the\nformer owners of the land and the water\nand the fruits and fishes thereof were\npermitted to do this. Never did an In\ndian fail to fulfill a wood contract and\nnever did the wood fail to burn ami\nI make a warm fire. Now the rule is\nthat wood that has been in the water\nshall not go into a soldier stove. Why\nis this, when dry spruce several years\ni ago was so near and is now so far? The\nI Indian does not savvy the horse and the\ni horse does not savvy the Indian; so the\nIndian cannot haul wood hut must bring\nit over the water or not at all. Not to\ntake wood that has been in the water is\nto not take the Indians\u2019 wood. Would\nthe commissioner have the embargo\nlifted from rafted wood?\nThe commissioner expressed sympa\nthy for his visitors and their people,\ncomplimented them for desiring to en\ngage in useful and profitable employ\nment, and told them that while it is ob\nligatory on him to put them in jail for\ninfractions of the law his jurisdiction\ndoes not extend over the fuel supply for\nthe army. However, he gave it as his\nprivate opinion that at the rate the\nnearby wood is being consumed fuel will\nhave to be brought in by water before\ni long. _\nSee Juck Cavanaugh for well water and\nj light express. Scavenger work a specialty.\n\nFalse Alarm of Hen\nDrowned on Beaver\nCharles Schick, whose friends in the\nFairbanks district believed he had been\ndrowned in Beaver river last month,\nfloated intoTanana in a small boat from\nthe Beaver country last Saturday at\nnoon. His partner \u201cTwo-Step\u201d Louis\nSchmidt, he said, was on his way across\ncountry from Beaver river to Fairbanks.\nNo accident had befallen them.\nThe apprehension for the safety of tlfe\nmen was caused by the return of their\ndog, in a starved condition, to McGuire\nand Chapman\u2019s camp, on Beaver, more\nthan a month after Schick and Schmidt\nhad left there.\nJUST-NEW GOODS-RECEIVED\nAt $4.00 WATCHES AT OUTSIDE PRICES To $110.00\nSouvenir Rings $3.00 to $12.50.\u2014Pins, Brooches, Bracelets, Charms\nand all Kinds of Souvenir Jewelry\nBEMIS\nWATCHMAKER, MANUFACTURING JEWELER\nNext Door to Postoffice\nOPTICIAN","height":"24224","width":"18096"}}
